title.narrative: OUTPUT 1.4: HEALTH FACILITIES CAPACITIES HAS STRENGHTEN FOR SAM CARE

description.narrative: Health facilities at national, regional and local levels have improved capacities to provide quality treatment to children (6-59 months) affected by SAM, particularly in the areas affected by food insecurity., which contributes to Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition (Covid), Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: 1. By 2022, newborns, children under-five, adolescents, and pregnant and lactating women, increasingly utilize quality health, nutrition HIV and Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH) services and families adopt healthy and hygienic behaviours and practices, including during emergencies.

description.narrative: En 2021 et malgré la situation COVID 19, l’UNICEF a contribué à la continuité des services essentiels de santé et de nutrition permettant à 3 250 enfants de moins de 5 ans souffrant de malnutrition aigüe sévères (MAS) sur les 4 000 cas attendus (80%) de recevoir les prises en charge adéquates grâce à la sécurisation des intrants, l’utilisation des réseaux communautaires pour les dépistages, la référence des cas et les sensibilisations des parents. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:06/01/2022
